The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Feb. 15 (PTI): An FIR need not mention the caste of the accused in cases relating to atrocities under the Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes Act, the Supreme Court has held.           
	A three-judge bench ruled that police can start investigation on the basis of a complaint from the alleged victim even if he or she fails to mention the caste of the accused.                   
	 Madurai (PTI): The moral police brigade in Tamil Nadus Theni district was in for a surprise when a couple asked them to arrange for their registered marriage when cornered by the activists on Valentines Day. Rajamanickam said he was prepared for the Sangh parivar activists.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): The Maharashtra government has decided to ban the use of mobile phones by teachers in schools to prevent wastage of precious education hours. The education department had received complaints from parents, the minister for school education, Patangrao Kadam said. Students too will be banned from using cellphones in school, Kadam said.                   
	 Jaisalmer (PTI): A farmer has filed a police complaint alleging that a plane dropped a bomb on his field in Jaisalmer close to the Indo-Pak border, damaging his house and crop. A joint team from the Indian Air Force and the Indian Army have reached           the spot.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): If an employees death is not connected in any way to his assigned duty, the victims family is not entitled to compensation, the Supreme Court has held. The case related to a truck driver who had drowned in a pond while taking a dip during trip, an official said.                  
	 Jammu (PTI): Over five lakh government employees in Jammu and Kashmir have decided to go on a three-day strike from Monday, following unsatisfactory response from the government to their pay hike demands. Chief minister Omar Abdullah will meet the agitating employees on Monday.                                                                                                                           
